Pokémon Go is a respectable hunt for health and happiness
It is fascinating to see how the world is changing.
Over the past decade, many have been concerned that teenagers and children no longer go out to play, but prefer to spend their free time watching screens.
Pokémon Go gets people to get up from the couch and take part in some activity.
The screen time was initially limited to television, then to video games, and now recently to smartphones.
It is therefore great to see that technology and outdoor activity do not exclude each other.
I refer, of course, to a fad called Pokémon Go. An application based on characters originally developed for video games in the 1990s (later they became a series of drawings, playing cards and other follow-up products).
Like many pop culture phenomena, its popularity was somewhat dilute before the release of this new game in the United States, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
After that, the release of the game in other countries was postponed, as huge popularity overloaded the servers.
In just days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as much as Twitter.
How does it work?
In a nutshell, players use their smartphones to search for Pokémon, which are tracked by GPS, and which can be “photographed” (by phone screen capture) or “catched” after discovery.
A generation that played the game when it was younger has joined the craze and jumped up from the couch to join the quests.
In the United States, the game has led to a significant increase in the “average person”’s daily steps.
The Apple Watch app Cardiogram, which follows 35 000 users, recently told the Washington Post that within two days of the release of the game, the number of people moving 30 minutes a day jumped from 45% to 53% for users followed by Cardiogram.
The company does not know who is playing Pokémon Go, it only sees the training level data.
Many public health campaigns have called for ‘find 30’, ‘get up on the couch’ and ‘be active every day’ to have made no difference because the majority of public health warnings are boring and caring for people who look unhappy.
However, the importance of physical activity cannot be underestimated.
People who move regularly have a lower risk of developing cancer or depression.
Activity helps with weight management, high blood pressure and diabetes. Its benefits are too diverse to be listed here.
The great thing about Pokémon Go is that it makes people go out and do something they enjoy.
This covers the three pillars of health: exercise, fresh air and sunshine, and fun.
Some people even make new friends when they hunt.
As usual, resentful spoilers are looking for things to complain about.
Yes, someone can walk towards the door.
So what?
There has been a breakthrough.
Although earlier there were applications like Fitbit that could track activity, they did not give reason to move in the same way as this game.
The charm of the novelty disappears and the use of it will fade in due course.
However, due to the success of Pokémon, there will be other games that combine applications and virtual reality with real-world activity, helping many people who are hunting to be more active, in better condition and healthier.
