In Häme, it has, among other things, obtained information on asylum seekers.
The most recent reform of working methods
The establishment of analysis units is the most recent reform of police working methods.
The aim has been to prevent crime, i.e. that the police would less and less often leave the straws in the mires only when they receive an alert.
With the information collected and analysed by the unit, day-to-day police operations are targeted where they are most needed.
Along with the reform of the police administration, a crime intelligence centre, its three national units and its own crime intelligence unit were established in the country.
The PTR Centre, which operates in connection with the Central Criminal Police in Vantaa, leads the operations nationally.
PTR units, as their name suggests, work with the Police, Customs and Border Guard.
The RTA units, on the other hand, work in shared areas according to the police departments, and their task is to provide information to both local police forces and national units.
Enquiry extends beyond your own territory
While the individual police is aware of what has happened during his 12-hour shift, the task of the RTA unit is to know what is going on throughout the police department.
The inquiry also extends beyond the boundaries of your own institution, because this is what crime does.
People working in the RTA unit have better computer skills than the basic police.
The unit uses registers, an alert function database and observations to draw the attention of the police to new phenomena, productive criminals or similar crimes.
This is called serialization and is one of the most important tools of criminal intelligence.
All people have their own way of working.
The handprint is also visible at work, whether it is honest or criminal.
On the basis of the method of action, a certain image is formed of the author.
Serialization can be done either on the basis of an act or on the basis of a person, depending on which of the police has more information.
Criminals learn from their mistakes
The employees of the RTA unit do not move up the collars in the city, but their work is not entirely public either.
The methods used by both individuals and criminals are not reported, as this could lead to professional criminals developing their activities and thus preventing crime prevention attempts by the police.
The police will publicly report on the methods if they are anticipated to pose a threat.
For example, in the early summer, such a case was reported as a way of marking empty dwellings used in apartment break-ins.
