Kepler measures the rotational speed of stars in the Pleiades
The mission of the latest Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers to compile the most complete list of the rotational speeds of the stars in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data will help astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at varying speeds, as well as how rotation times are associated with planet formation.
We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will now learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age and even the history of its solar system,” said Luisa Rebull, researcher at the Pasadena Centre for infrared processing and analysis at Caltech.
The Pleiadian star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster were born about 125 million years ago, and are just now reaching adulthood.
They are now spinning at their top level.
At its peak speed, these adult stars are plunged by large amounts of star wind.
When these winds pass through the magnetic fields of the stars, they brake the stars.
As the star ages, its rotational speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of each star by tracking the appearance of identifiable star spots, such as sun spots.
The latest list of star speeds suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, from whom bigger ones make devils slower than smaller ones.
In the “ballet” of the Pleiades, we see that slow spinners are usually more massive, while the fastest spinners are usually very light stars,” Rebull said.
Since the Plejade star cluster is so close, it is an ideal cosmic laboratory for estimating the properties of stars at rotational speeds.
The Pleiadian star cluster provides an anchor for the theoretical models of star rotation, which include both directions, younger and older,” Rebull said.
We still have a lot to learn about how, because and why stars slow down their speed of rotation and so to speak, hang their ‘dance shoes’ on a nail.
Rebull and his colleagues described their latest analysis of Plejade rotation rates in three articles, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
